The Vasari Corridor – a new view of Florence|https://www.circoloitaliano.org.nz/blog-1/the-vasari-corridor-a-new-view-of-florence|eight-year closure, the Vasari Corridor (or Corridoio Vasariano) opened to the general public for the first  ...    This extraordinary corridor was the work of Renaissance architect, artist and biographer, Giorgio Vasari, (who also designed the Uffizi Galleries) as a private passageway enabling Duke Cosimo I de’ Medici to move between his offices in the Uffizi to his residence in the Pitti Palace unobserved. Vasari completed the corridor in five months in 1565. Its 750-metre route starts inside the Uffizi, runs along the Arno River and over the top of the Ponte Vecchio, through the church of San Felice (where the Medici family could gaze directly down into the church and attend mass without causing  ...    The recent
